4 DAYS UNTIL SELFHEALERS CIRCLE ENROLLMENT 🎉

Thanks to member feedback, we’ve spent the past year building our own hosting platform. It’s easier to navigate + we now have a private community outside of facebook. Members are loving our new space.

The cost is $26/month or $286/year (one month free). My goal has always been to make the Circle affordable + accessible.

Enrollment will open January 1st at 12pm PST. Spaces are limited + do SELL OUT quickly. If you’re on the waitlist, you’ll be sent a link a few moments before enrollment opens. It might be helpful to set an alarm. There are currently 30,000+ people on the waitlist.

To find complete details on what the circle is all about, click the link in my bio. You can also add yourself to the waitlist.

I’ll see you in the ⭕️ + cannot wait for your healing journey to begin! selfhealers

node.text: Today it’s a true honor to talk to @dr.editheger— I’m actually a bit overwhelmed post filming this. Edith is a psychologist + Holocaust survivor who just released the book “The Gift.” I got chills throughout the book + know members of this community will love every word. Edith is an embodied teacher who gifts us with the wisdom that we are not not victims of our past, but powerful creators of our future. Her story is a testament to our true human potential. She’s a gift. I hope you all enjoy #selfhealers

May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Our Own Body Image Is Created By: @the.holistic.psychologist The way our parent figures speak about their body The way our parent figures speaks about, compares, +describes other people's bodies The way parent figures directly speak about/describe our own bodies The way our earliest peers talk about our bodies + the bodies of others (from their own conditioning The way bodies are spoken about in media + within commercials'.

node.text:
Body image has nothing to do with our physical appearance.

Body image lives within the mind. 

It’s the internalized thoughts, beliefs, preferences that we were either directly told or heard in childhood.

Our parent figures have the greatest impact on our own body image. 

How they speak about their bodies, speak about other people’s bodies, + our own body becomes our body image.

When we reach school age, have peers who also project ideas about body image (the same ideas they’ve heard at home.) 

We also get messages from media (the collective body image) that reinforces the same ideas heard within our homes.

I’m still in the process of learning to love my body. 

For me, it was helpful to go back to my moms messaging of her own body. She always struggled with weight. She also always commented on the weight of other women. How they’d put on weight. How they’d lost weight. On my sisters weight. I was conscious from a young age that appearance was very important + spoken about often.

Diets were also incredibly common in my home. Crash diets— *not* addressing nutrition, or eating through listening to the body. Losing weight was always a goal, but actually feeling good was not spoken of.

The message: the body is only to be loved + accepted at a specific weight. When the body is not that weight, it’s hated or loathed, or rejected.

How did you hear your parent figures speak about weight, their bodies, + your body? #selfhealers

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Nicole LePera on July 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Codependency is chronic neglect of Self that creates resentment @the.holistic.psychologist'.

node.text:
Resentment is a clear message. It’s a sign that we haven’t set boundaries, that our boundaries have been violated, or that we’ve been playing a role (caretaker, rescuer, ‘fixer’ in order to be loved.)

We learn codependent dynamics when we are children + have to think of our parent figures emotions, be hypervigilant to their moods, + to be a version of ourselves that gains the approval from them we desperately want.

Codependency says: “how you feel about me, is how I feel about me.”

Thanks why healing is self reclamation.

Remember:

1. You can + should say no to things that make you feel resentment 

2. You do not need to overexplain or make excuses for your needs 

3. Boundaries are kind + create safe relationships 

4. You are not responsible for the emotional states of others

5. People’s perceptions of you are not the truth of who you are #selfhealers

node.text:
Addiction isn’t about the substance.

We teach kids about the dangers of drugs. To avoid them. Without understanding what drives people to use them.

Our greatest need is to be seen, heard, loved, + authentically expressed. We need this the most from our parent figures, who our survival depends on.

If that parent has their own trauma, they have a distorted self image. 

This self image impacts the relationship they have with their child. With distorted self image comes emotional neglect, lack of boundaries, + shaming, rage, shut down, + many other dysfunctional coping behaviors.

This distorted self image is passed on generationally. 

Children internalize the belief that something is wrong with them. 

If our own parent doesn’t love or accept us it means we are unloveable. 

Children don’t have the ability understand behavior is how a person feels about themselves— they personalize behavior.

This wounding has us enter dysfunctional relationships, self sabotage, + continue to betray ourselves. 

Using substances is the only way we see to escape this pain.

Being within the cycle of addiction is a living nightmare. 

There’s shame, rejection, abandonment— + it makes perfect sense because it’s re-creation of the same childhood painful environment. 

Until we heal the root cause of addition (the painful childhood wounding) we will continue to see addiction. 

Fear tactics, punishment, + the “war on drugs” have failed miserably. For good reason— shame is WHY people turn to drugs. 

Add more shame + you get more people using.

The “gateway” drug is the lack of safe/secure attachment we all need as children.

The “gateway” drug is a dysregulated nervous system. 

The “gateway” drug is a society that rejects talents, people, + ideas that are out of the mainstream accepted narrative #selfhealers

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Nicole LePera in Los Angeles, California. May be an image of 2 people and outdoors.

node.text:
The photo on the left is me 9 years ago. I know that version of myself but I barely remember her life.

At the time, I was living in New York in the process of getting my PhD. I was completely dissociated, struggling with unresolved trauma I wasn’t even aware of. 

I hadn’t been trained to even understand trauma other than war or extreme assault. 

How would I understand my own?

Self care didn’t exist in my life. I coped through binge drinking, barely slept, had no awareness of my body— the foods I ate or the way I moved it. I was sleep walking through life, neglecting + betraying myself. Re-living the patterns I’d been conditioned in. Fully committed to my story of lack + limitation. 

I spent most of my time distracting myself  in any way I could. Running from accomplishment to accomplishment or relationship to relationship.

Running from myself.

In the home I was conditioned in, there was no talk of potential, of hope, of purpose, or of self ownership. Those things weren’t for me. I was modeled limitations— + those limitations became my “reality.”

After my own dark night of the soul, I went on a spiritual journey. 

A journey of re-conditioning my mind + body. Of protecting my energy, honoring my limits, + speaking my truth. I stepped away from the paradigm of “mental illness” I’d been trained in to share what I both taught myself + continue to practice in my own life. 

My confidence grew + for the first time in my adult life I knew what it felt like to believe in myself.

To believe the truth that I’ve come to know: we are all our OWN best healers.

Inside every single one of us is a light. A deep inner knowing. A grounded, loving presence waiting to be witnessed + expressed #selfhealers

node.text:
I believe no conditioning causes more pain, suffering, + confusion that the conditioning we have accepted as a society around marriage/relationships.

There is a belief that our partners should meet all of our needs, + that it should be a romantic/whimsical experience that naturally works itself out.

Relationships are work. 

They’re mostly *self* work because the connection we have to + with ourselves impacts every relationship we have. The trust we have for self, becomes the truth we have (or don’t have) for another.

Most adults have attachment wounding which leads to insecurity, a deep belief of unworthiness, + a fear of abandonment.

Because of this, couples aren’t actually even arguing about the present moment (the dishes in the sink, what school the kids should go to, how money is spent.) 

They’re re-enacting that childhood wounding: attempting to be seen/heard, controlling each other unconsciously, keeping score of each other’s actions, focusing on each others perceived flaws + how those flaws need to change.

When you witness yourself or other couples “fly off the handlebars” at each other, they’re in the midst of the trauma body— feeling the past pain flood through their body. 

If one of them says they’re overreacting or dramatic (typically what a parent figure said) the emotional reactivity just becomes stronger.

Few of us have witnessed healthy relationships where there are boundaries, clear communication, freedom to authentically express, + the ability to emotionally regulate during conflict.

What we witness, we repeat.

Marriage has been a beautiful challenge for me. 

It’s been a space where I’ve been able to unlearn deep codependent dynamics, take ownership of my emotions, + have someone hold up a mirror to see the “dark” parts of myself— the parts often denied. The parts often looked away from. The parts of me that want to blame + project.

At times it’s a beautiful space of freedom, evolution, + joy. At times it’s a space of disappointment, boredom, + a full blown nightmare for the ego.

Creating the relationships we want takes healing, brutal self awareness, + radical self accountability #selfhealers

node.text:
Therapists are running a business + when you choose to hire a therapist, it’s important to ask questions. 

A confident therapist will welcome them. Advocate for your healing: 

1. Have you been on your own personal healing journey? 

2. Do you have a professional social media page? (Note: therapists have a right to keep their private life, private. If they have an account for work, check out the content. See if it resonates. Also witness how they interact with others/use their platform) 

2. What is your understanding of trauma? (Trauma is about the impact on the nervous system, not the event itself— a common misunderstanding in the therapy world)

3. Do you work with attachment + understand childhood trauma + how it manifests in adulthood? (I have noticed many therapists online dismiss, invalidate, or downplay childhood experiences. If a therapists invalidates your trauma OR tells you you’re “too traumatized,” it’s a sign they are not comfortable, not a reflection of you.

4. Do you work with the nervous system? Will you give me tools to help regulate my emotions?

5. I’m (gay, trans, BIPOC, in a polyamory relationship, etc.). I share experiences around this— are you comfortable/have you worked with people like this?

6. I am going through a spiritual awakening/dark night of the soul. It’s a painful stage of healing. Can I talk with you about that? (Note: last year a therapist with a large following took a dark night of the soul post of mine + re-shared it with his following with clown emojis over it. While this post spoke to his own emotional maturity, it made me think: what would happen in a therapy room if someone shared their spiritual experiences. We are mind, body, + soul + mocking spiritual experiences is a red flag.)

7. What do you believe about/what is your view about the world? 

8. “I have been following, reading, learning more about x. What are your thoughts on that?” The therapist should be open + receptive. Red flags: defensiveness or rejection of idea you’re drawn to.

9. Do you continue to learn, read, + study around healing trauma? Good therapists are always learning new information + integregtating it on their own path #selfhealers

node.text:
I’m fortunate enough that my work is my life passion + most of my down time I self study. Here’s recent favorites:

1. “NO BAD PARTS” Dr. Richard Schwartz. IFS is founded on the belief that we each have a “self” or what I call the authentic self + various other developmentally young parts of ourselves that are traumatized + need healing. The book is a compassionate approach of loving all parts of ourselves + meeting them with curiosity. It takes a macro approach that even the most dysfunctional parts of ourselves are terrified protectors that are looking to seen + released from a job they no longer need to do.

2. SOMATIC INTERNAL FAMILY SYSTEMS THEORY by Susan Mcconell: We cannot talk our way out of trauma + the body must be brought into treatment. This book is a must read for learning how to heal through the body. 

3. BECOMING SAFTEY EMBODIED by Diedre Fay: a must read for those doing self work to integrate mind, body, + soul. Our first attachments create how we feel about ourselves, others, + the world. This book teaches us how to create safety + heal our world.

4. INNER BONDING BECOMING A LOVING ADULT TO YOUR INNER CHILD by Dr. Margaret Paul: One of the best books hands down on inner child healing. The workbook is amazing too.

5. SELF THERAPY by. Dr. Jay Earley: a guide to healing yourself. Incredibly practical + helpful for anyone on a healing journey.

6. CHILDHOOD DISRUPTED by Donna Jackson Nakazawa: A paradigm shifting book on how childhood trauma impacts your genetic expression, how we inherit biology through the environments we are raised in + how to heal. 

7. SET BOUNDARIES, FIND PEACE by Nedra Glover Tawwab: Nedra is a gifted content creator. I’ve been following her since I first came to Instagram + admire her simplistic + practical teaching on boundaries. In my opinion, boundaries are key in reclaiming our spiritual self. Her book is just like her instagram teaching: clear + enlightening

8. TRANSCENDING TRAUMA by Dr. Frank Anderson: cried a few times through this one. Beautifully done. A true guide to understanding the inner child (young parts of self) + how you can take the journey of healing + loving yourself #selfhealere
